section_description: Cardiac malformations occur in 75% of patients, most commonly tetralogy of Fallot, interrupted aortic arch type B, ventricular septal defect, and truncus arteriosus.

parent_description: Reduction in all blood cell lines due to bone marrow replacement and consumptive coagulopathy.

section_description: Progressive thickening of the heart muscle, particularly the left ventricle, is the most common and severe manifestation of Danon disease. parent_description: Weakness of skeletal muscles, particularly proximal muscles, is common in Danon disease. Muscle biopsy shows autophagic vacuoles with sarcolemmal features. This can cause difficulty with physical activities and may be progressive.

section_description: Cognitive impairment of variable severity is frequently observed in affected males, ranging from mild learning difficulties to more significant intellectual disability. This is part of the classic clinical triad in male patients.
parent_description: Cognitive impairment of variable severity is frequently observed in affected males, ranging from mild learning difficulties to more significant intellectual disability. This is part of the classic clinical triad in male patients.

section_description: Ventricular pre-excitation due to accessory atrioventricular electrical conduction pathways is frequently observed in Danon disease patients. This cardiac conduction abnormality may precede overt cardiomyopathy.
parent_description: Ventricular pre-excitation due to accessory atrioventricular electrical conduction pathways is frequently observed in Danon disease patients. This cardiac conduction abnormality may precede overt cardiomyopathy.

section_description: Photoreceptor and retinal pigment epithelium degeneration has been reported in some Danon disease patients, presenting as cone-rod dystrophy and progressive visual impairment.
parent_description: Photoreceptor and retinal pigment epithelium degeneration has been reported in some Danon disease patients, presenting as cone-rod dystrophy and progressive visual impairment.

section_description: A slow-growing dermal plaque or nodule that progressively enlarges over months to years. The tumor often has a protuberant or multinodular surface and may be skin-colored, red-brown, or violaceous.
parent_description: A slow-growing dermal plaque or nodule that progressively enlarges over months to years. The tumor often has a protuberant or multinodular surface and may be skin-colored, red-brown, or violaceous.

section_description: As the tumor grows, it may form a larger soft tissue mass extending into subcutaneous tissues. The tumor has an infiltrative growth pattern.
parent_description: As the tumor grows, it may form a larger soft tissue mass extending into subcutaneous tissues. The tumor has an infiltrative growth pattern.

section_description: High rates of local recurrence (20-50%) occur after inadequate excision due to the infiltrative growth pattern with subclinical extension beyond visible tumor margins.
parent_description: High rates of local recurrence (20-50%) occur after inadequate excision due to the infiltrative growth pattern with subclinical extension beyond visible tumor margins.

section_description: Bulky abdominal masses are the hallmark presentation. Tumors are typically large and multiple at diagnosis, studding the peritoneal surfaces.
parent_description: Bulky abdominal masses are the hallmark presentation. Tumors are typically large and multiple at diagnosis, studding the peritoneal surfaces.

section_description: Malignant ascites is common due to extensive peritoneal involvement.
parent_description: Malignant ascites is common due to extensive peritoneal involvement.

section_description: Weight loss and cachexia are common with advanced disease burden.
parent_description: Weight loss and cachexia are common with advanced disease burden.

section_description: Fever may occur as a paraneoplastic symptom or with tumor necrosis.
parent_description: Fever may occur as a paraneoplastic symptom or with tumor necrosis.

section_description: Metastases to liver, lung, and lymph nodes are common. Most patients have disseminated disease at diagnosis given the diffuse peritoneal involvement.
parent_description: Metastases to liver, lung, and lymph nodes are common. Most patients have disseminated disease at diagnosis given the diffuse peritoneal involvement.

section_description: Rapidly enlarging lymphadenopathy is the most common presentation. Nodal disease may be localized or widespread.
parent_description: Rapidly enlarging lymphadenopathy is the most common presentation. Nodal disease may be localized or widespread.

section_description: B symptoms including drenching night sweats indicate active disease and are incorporated into staging.
parent_description: B symptoms including drenching night sweats indicate active disease and are incorporated into staging.

section_description: Unintentional weight loss greater than 10% body weight in 6 months is a B symptom with prognostic significance.
parent_description: Unintentional weight loss greater than 10% body weight in 6 months is a B symptom with prognostic significance.

section_description: Fatigue from disease burden, cytokine release, and anemia.
parent_description: Fatigue from disease burden, cytokine release, and anemia.

section_description: Spleen involvement occurs in some cases, particularly with advanced stage disease.
parent_description: Spleen involvement occurs in some cases, particularly with advanced stage disease.

section_description: Anemia may result from bone marrow infiltration, hemolysis, or cytokine effects.
parent_description: Anemia may result from bone marrow infiltration, hemolysis, or cytokine effects.

section_description: Persistent pain localized to the back.
parent_description: Persistent pain localized to the back.

section_description: Treatment-resistant seizures beginning in the first year of life, often triggered by fever, with progression to multiple seizure types.
parent_description: Treatment-resistant seizures beginning in the first year of life, often triggered by fever, with progression to multiple seizure types.

section_description: Progressive developmental regression typically beginning after seizure onset, affecting motor, language, and social skills.
parent_description: Progressive developmental regression typically beginning after seizure onset, affecting motor, language, and social skills.

section_description: Cognitive impairment ranging from mild to severe, often progressive in nature.
parent_description: Cognitive impairment ranging from mild to severe, often progressive in nature.

section_description: Behavioral difficulties including hyperactivity and attention deficits.
parent_description: Behavioral difficulties including hyperactivity and attention deficits.

section_description: Seizures triggered by fever, typically the presenting feature in infancy between 3 months and 6 years. Often prolonged hemiclonic seizures or status epilepticus.
parent_description: Seizures triggered by fever, typically the presenting feature in infancy between 3 months and 6 years. Often prolonged hemiclonic seizures or status epilepticus.

parent_description: Impaired coordination and balance, including gait abnormalities such as crouch gait. Motor impairment characteristic of Dravet syndrome.

section_description: Autism spectrum features including impaired social interaction, communication difficulties, and restricted repetitive behaviors.
parent_description: Autism spectrum features including impaired social interaction, communication difficulties, and restricted repetitive behaviors.

section_description: Postictal respiratory compromise and sleep-associated breathing abnormalities contributing to SUDEP risk.
parent_description: Postictal respiratory compromise and sleep-associated breathing abnormalities contributing to SUDEP risk.

section_description: Markedly elevated risk of sudden unexpected death in epilepsy (SUDEP), accounting for up to 50% of deaths in Dravet syndrome. Linked to seizure burden, postictal cardiorespiratory dysfunction, and potential cardiac susceptibility.

section_description: Epigastric pain is a common presenting symptom, often initially attributed to dyspepsia or gastritis.
parent_description: Epigastric pain is a common presenting symptom, often initially attributed to dyspepsia or gastritis.

section_description: Unintentional weight loss occurs due to decreased appetite and metabolic effects of malignancy.
parent_description: Unintentional weight loss occurs due to decreased appetite and metabolic effects of malignancy.

section_description: Generalized fatigue related to chronic disease and often anemia from occult gastrointestinal blood loss.
parent_description: Generalized fatigue related to chronic disease and often anemia from occult gastrointestinal blood loss.

section_description: Iron deficiency anemia from chronic gastrointestinal blood loss is common.
parent_description: Iron deficiency anemia from chronic gastrointestinal blood loss is common.

section_description: Liver enlargement may indicate metastatic disease.
parent_description: Liver enlargement may indicate metastatic disease.

section_description: Regional lymph node enlargement occurs with local spread.
parent_description: Regional lymph node enlargement occurs with local spread.

section_description: EGFR-mutant NSCLC is predominantly adenocarcinoma histology. Often presents as peripheral lung nodules with ground-glass or lepidic growth patterns.
parent_description: EGFR-mutant NSCLC is predominantly adenocarcinoma histology. Often presents as peripheral lung nodules with ground-glass or lepidic growth patterns.

section_description: EGFR mutations are strongly associated with never-smoking or light smoking history. The tumor develops through different carcinogenic pathways than smoking-associated lung cancer.
parent_description: EGFR mutations are strongly associated with never-smoking or light smoking history. The tumor develops through different carcinogenic pathways than smoking-associated lung cancer.

parent_description: Brain metastases occur in approximately 25-40% of EGFR-mutant NSCLC patients, often at presentation or during disease course. CNS-penetrant TKIs (osimertinib) have improved CNS disease control.

section_description: ER+ breast cancers are typically invasive ductal or lobular carcinomas. Luminal A tumors are often lower grade with favorable histologic features.
parent_description: ER+ breast cancers are typically invasive ductal or lobular carcinomas. Luminal A tumors are often lower grade with favorable histologic features.

section_description: Defining feature is ER expression 1% by immunohistochemistry. Higher ER expression (>10%) correlates with greater endocrine sensitivity. PR expression often accompanies ER positivity and indicates functional ER signaling.
parent_description: Defining feature is ER expression 1% by immunohistochemistry. Higher ER expression (>10%) correlates with greater endocrine sensitivity. PR expression often accompanies ER positivity and indicates functional ER signaling.

section_description: Unlike TNBC, ER+ breast cancer can recur many years (10-20+) after initial diagnosis, necessitating long-term surveillance and extended adjuvant endocrine therapy.
parent_description: Unlike TNBC, ER+ breast cancer can recur many years (10-20+) after initial diagnosis, necessitating long-term surveillance and extended adjuvant endocrine therapy.

section_description: Abnormally increased range of motion in multiple joints due to lax connective tissue.
parent_description: Abnormally increased range of motion in multiple joints due to lax connective tissue.

section_description: Abnormal bulging of the mitral valve leaflets into the left atrium during systole due to connective tissue laxity.
parent_description: Abnormal bulging of the mitral valve leaflets into the left atrium during systole due to connective tissue laxity.

section_description: Backflow of stomach contents into the esophagus, possibly related to laxity of the lower esophageal sphincter.
parent_description: Backflow of stomach contents into the esophagus, possibly related to laxity of the lower esophageal sphincter.

section_description: Fleshy, scar-associated lesions that develop over pressure points and areas of repeated trauma.
parent_description: Fleshy, scar-associated lesions that develop over pressure points and areas of repeated trauma.

section_description: Nearsightedness, a refractive error where distant objects appear blurred.
parent_description: Nearsightedness, a refractive error where distant objects appear blurred.

section_description: Repeated episodes of joints becoming displaced from their normal positions.
parent_description: Repeated episodes of joints becoming displaced from their normal positions.

section_description: Persistent pain in multiple joints resulting from joint instability, subluxations, and degenerative changes.
parent_description: Persistent pain in multiple joints resulting from joint instability, subluxations, and degenerative changes.

section_description: Prolonged time for wounds to heal with impaired re-epithelialization and abnormal granulation tissue formation.
parent_description: Prolonged time for wounds to heal with impaired re-epithelialization and abnormal granulation tissue formation.

section_description: A soft tissue mass is the most common presentation. Location varies by age and subtype, with head and neck common in younger children and genitourinary sites in adolescents.
parent_description: A soft tissue mass is the most common presentation. Location varies by age and subtype, with head and neck common in younger children and genitourinary sites in adolescents.

section_description: Orbital ERMS commonly presents with proptosis and is associated with excellent prognosis. The orbit is a favorable primary site.
parent_description: Orbital ERMS commonly presents with proptosis and is associated with excellent prognosis. The orbit is a favorable primary site.

section_description: Bladder or prostate ERMS may present with hematuria or urinary obstruction.
parent_description: Bladder or prostate ERMS may present with hematuria or urinary obstruction.

section_description: Weight loss and failure to thrive may occur with advanced disease.
parent_description: Weight loss and failure to thrive may occur with advanced disease.

section_description: Persistent platelet count of 450,000/uL or greater is a diagnostic criterion. Many patients have counts exceeding 1,000,000/uL at diagnosis.
parent_description: Persistent platelet count of 450,000/uL or greater is a diagnostic criterion. Many patients have counts exceeding 1,000,000/uL at diagnosis.

section_description: Arterial and venous thrombotic events are the major disease complications. Includes stroke, myocardial infarction, peripheral arterial occlusion, and deep vein thrombosis.
parent_description: Arterial and venous thrombotic events are the major disease complications. Includes stroke, myocardial infarction, peripheral arterial occlusion, and deep vein thrombosis.

section_description: Headaches are common and may reflect microvascular disturbance. Erythromelalgia-associated headache responds well to aspirin.
parent_description: Headaches are common and may reflect microvascular disturbance. Erythromelalgia-associated headache responds well to aspirin.

section_description: Burning pain, redness, and warmth in extremities due to platelet-mediated arteriolar inflammation. Highly responsive to aspirin therapy.
parent_description: Burning pain, redness, and warmth in extremities due to platelet-mediated arteriolar inflammation. Highly responsive to aspirin therapy.

section_description: Mild splenomegaly may be present but is less prominent than in polycythemia vera or primary myelofibrosis. Marked splenomegaly suggests transformation.
parent_description: Mild splenomegaly may be present but is less prominent than in polycythemia vera or primary myelofibrosis. Marked splenomegaly suggests transformation.

section_description: Fatigue and reduced quality of life are common despite the generally indolent disease course.
parent_description: Fatigue and reduced quality of life are common despite the generally indolent disease course.

section_description: Localized bone pain is the most common presenting symptom, often present for weeks to months before diagnosis. Pain may be intermittent initially and worsen progressively.
parent_description: Localized bone pain is the most common presenting symptom, often present for weeks to months before diagnosis. Pain may be intermittent initially and worsen progressively.

section_description: A palpable mass may develop as tumor extends through the bone cortex into surrounding soft tissues. The mass is often firm and may be tender.
parent_description: A palpable mass may develop as tumor extends through the bone cortex into surrounding soft tissues. The mass is often firm and may be tender.

section_description: Systemic symptoms including fever may occur, sometimes leading to initial misdiagnosis as osteomyelitis.

section_description: Unintentional weight loss may occur with advanced or metastatic disease.

section_description: Approximately 25% of patients have metastases at diagnosis, most commonly to lungs, bone, and bone marrow. Metastatic disease significantly worsens prognosis.
parent_description: Approximately 25% of patients have metastases at diagnosis, most commonly to lungs, bone, and bone marrow. Metastatic disease significantly worsens prognosis.

section_description: Jaundice from biliary obstruction or extensive hepatic involvement. Less common in intrahepatic than in perihilar cholangiocarcinoma.
parent_description: Jaundice from biliary obstruction or extensive hepatic involvement. Less common in intrahepatic than in perihilar cholangiocarcinoma.

section_description: Nausea from hepatic dysfunction or as a treatment-related side effect.
parent_description: Nausea from hepatic dysfunction or as a treatment-related side effect.

section_description: Gross or microscopic hematuria is the most common presenting symptom of urothelial carcinoma. May be intermittent and painless initially.
parent_description: Gross or microscopic hematuria is the most common presenting symptom of urothelial carcinoma. May be intermittent and painless initially.

section_description: Painful urination may occur due to bladder irritation or tumor involvement. Often associated with urinary frequency and urgency.
parent_description: Painful urination may occur due to bladder irritation or tumor involvement. Often associated with urinary frequency and urgency.

section_description: Constitutional symptoms including fatigue are common in advanced disease and may be related to anemia from chronic blood loss.
parent_description: Constitutional symptoms including fatigue are common in advanced disease and may be related to anemia from chronic blood loss.

parent_description: Elevated white blood cell count is particularly common in FLT3-ITD AML, often exceeding 100,000/uL, reflecting the proliferative nature of the disease.

section_description: Normocytic normochromic anemia results from bone marrow replacement by leukemic blasts and ineffective erythropoiesis.
parent_description: Normocytic normochromic anemia results from bone marrow replacement by leukemic blasts and ineffective erythropoiesis.

section_description: Low platelet count due to bone marrow failure, contributing to bleeding risk.
parent_description: Low platelet count due to bone marrow failure, contributing to bleeding risk.

parent_description: Increased susceptibility to bacterial and fungal infections due to neutropenia from bone marrow failure.

section_description: Easy bruising, petechiae, mucosal bleeding, and prolonged bleeding from minor wounds due to thrombocytopenia.
parent_description: Easy bruising, petechiae, mucosal bleeding, and prolonged bleeding from minor wounds due to thrombocytopenia.

section_description: Severe, burning pain affecting the extremities, particularly hands and feet, often the earliest clinical manifestation. Pain crises can be disabling. Pathophysiology involves neuronal sensitization from lyso-Gb3 effects and lysosomal dysfunction.
parent_description: Severe, burning pain affecting the extremities, particularly hands and feet, often the earliest clinical manifestation. Pain crises can be disabling. Pathophysiology involves neuronal sensitization from lyso-Gb3 effects and lysosomal dysfunction.

section_description: Small, dark red skin lesions that cluster in the lower trunk and genital region. These are pathognomonic cutaneous manifestations of Fabry disease resulting from vascular dilatation with epidermal hyperkeratosis.
parent_description: Small, dark red skin lesions that cluster in the lower trunk and genital region. These are pathognomonic cutaneous manifestations of Fabry disease resulting from vascular dilatation with epidermal hyperkeratosis.

section_description: Urinary protein excretion, often the earliest sign of Fabry nephropathy. Progresses from microalbuminuria to overt proteinuria. Results from podocyte injury due to Gb3/lyso-Gb3 accumulation, autophagy impairment, and inflammatory signaling.
parent_description: Urinary protein excretion, often the earliest sign of Fabry nephropathy. Progresses from microalbuminuria to overt proteinuria. Results from podocyte injury due to Gb3/lyso-Gb3 accumulation, autophagy impairment, and inflammatory signaling.

parent_description: Progressive renal dysfunction leading to end-stage renal disease. Driven by podocyte loss, glomerulosclerosis, tubulointerstitial fibrosis, and persistent inflammation.

section_description: Concentric hypertrophy of the left ventricle resulting from cardiomyocyte lipid accumulation, oxidative stress, inflammation, and fibrosis. Increases arrhythmia risk and may progress to heart failure.
parent_description: Concentric hypertrophy of the left ventricle resulting from cardiomyocyte lipid accumulation, oxidative stress, inflammation, and fibrosis. Increases arrhythmia risk and may progress to heart failure.

section_description: Atrial fibrillation and ventricular arrhythmias result from cardiomyocyte hypertrophy, fibrosis, and inflammatory remodeling that create arrhythmogenic substrate.
parent_description: Atrial fibrillation and ventricular arrhythmias result from cardiomyocyte hypertrophy, fibrosis, and inflammatory remodeling that create arrhythmogenic substrate.

section_description: Increased risk of ischemic stroke and transient ischemic attacks due to cerebrovascular dysfunction from endothelial dysfunction, microvascular remodeling, and pro-thrombotic state.
parent_description: Increased risk of ischemic stroke and transient ischemic attacks due to cerebrovascular dysfunction from endothelial dysfunction, microvascular remodeling, and pro-thrombotic state.

section_description: Hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps carpet the colon and rectum. Polyps typically appear in adolescence in classic FAP. The number and density of polyps correlates with mutation location in APC.
parent_description: Hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps carpet the colon and rectum. Polyps typically appear in adolescence in classic FAP. The number and density of polyps correlates with mutation location in APC.

parent_description: Without prophylactic surgery, colorectal cancer develops in nearly 100% of patients with classic FAP, typically by age 40. The average age of cancer diagnosis is 39 years without surveillance/intervention.

section_description: Epigastric pain or discomfort is the most common presenting symptom, often initially attributed to dyspepsia or peptic ulcer disease.
parent_description: Epigastric pain or discomfort is the most common presenting symptom, often initially attributed to dyspepsia or peptic ulcer disease.

section_description: Ulceration of the gastric mucosa.

section_description: Large tumors may cause partial or complete intestinal obstruction, particularly in the small bowel.

disorder_name: Hereditary Breast and Ovarian Cancer Syndrome
section_description: Breast cancer risk is 70-80% for BRCA1 and 60-70% for BRCA2 mutation carriers. BRCA1-associated breast cancers are often triple-negative (ER-/PR-/HER2-) and high grade. BRCA2-associated breast cancers more often express hormone receptors. Risk of contralateral breast cancer is significantly elevated.

BRCA2-associated breast cancers more often express hormone receptors. Risk of contralateral breast cancer is significantly elevated.

disorder_name: Hereditary Breast and Ovarian Cancer Syndrome
section_description: Ovarian cancer risk is 40-50% for BRCA1 and 15-30% for BRCA2 mutation carriers. Most are high-grade serous carcinomas. Typically presents at earlier ages than sporadic ovarian cancer. Risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy is often recommended.

disorder_name: Hereditary Breast and Ovarian Cancer Syndrome
section_description: Lifetime risk of pancreatic cancer is increased to approximately 2-7%, particularly with BRCA2 mutations. BRCA2 is a recognized pancreatic cancer susceptibility gene. Surveillance may be considered in families with pancreatic cancer history.

disorder_name: Hereditary Breast and Ovarian Cancer Syndrome

section_description: Life-threatening tear in the aortic wall allowing blood to enter between tissue layers, the leading cause of death in untreated Marfan syndrome.
parent_description: Life-threatening tear in the aortic wall allowing blood to enter between tissue layers, the leading cause of death in untreated Marfan syndrome.
description: Tear in the inner layer of the aortic wall allowing blood to flow between layers.
raw_json: {"description": "Tear in the inner layer of the aortic wall allowing blood to flow between layers.", "preferred_term": "Aortic Dissection", "term": {"id": "HP:0002647", "label": "Aortic dissection"}}

section_description: Myxomatous degeneration of mitral valve leaflets causing prolapse into the left atrium during systole, often accompanied by mitral regurgitation.
parent_description: Myxomatous degeneration of mitral valve leaflets causing prolapse into the left atrium during systole, often accompanied by mitral regurgitation.
description: Abnormal systolic displacement of mitral valve leaflets into the left atrium.
raw_json: {"description": "Abnormal systolic displacement of mitral valve leaflets into the left atrium.", "preferred_term": "Mitral valve prolapse", "term": {"id": "HP:0001634", "label": "Mitral valve prolapse"}}

section_description: Progressive enlargement of the aortic root diameter, typically measured by echocardiography and tracked using Z-scores adjusted for age and body surface area.
parent_description: Progressive enlargement of the aortic root diameter, typically measured by echocardiography and tracked using Z-scores adjusted for age and body surface area.
description: Abnormal widening of the aortic root.
raw_json: {"description": "Abnormal widening of the aortic root.", "preferred_term": "Aortic root aneurysm", "term": {"id": "HP:0002616", "label": "Aortic root aneurysm"}}

section_description: MTC typically presents as a firm, painless thyroid nodule. In hereditary cases, bilateral or multifocal disease may be present at diagnosis.
parent_description: MTC typically presents as a firm, painless thyroid nodule. In hereditary cases, bilateral or multifocal disease may be present at diagnosis.

section_description: Secretory diarrhea occurs in advanced MTC due to tumor secretion of vasoactive substances including calcitonin and prostaglandins.
parent_description: Secretory diarrhea occurs in advanced MTC due to tumor secretion of vasoactive substances including calcitonin and prostaglandins.

section_description: Cervical lymph node involvement is common at diagnosis. The extent of nodal disease affects prognosis and surgical planning.
parent_description: Cervical lymph node involvement is common at diagnosis. The extent of nodal disease affects prognosis and surgical planning.

section_description: Headache from increased intracranial pressure due to obstructive hydrocephalus. Often worse in morning.
parent_description: Headache from increased intracranial pressure due to obstructive hydrocephalus. Often worse in morning.

section_description: Cerebellar ataxia with appendicular (limb) involvement when tumor is lateral, or truncal instability with midline tumors.
parent_description: Cerebellar ataxia with appendicular (limb) involvement when tumor is lateral, or truncal instability with midline tumors.

section_description: Vomiting from increased intracranial pressure, often in the morning.
parent_description: Vomiting from increased intracranial pressure, often in the morning.

section_description: Increased head circumference in infants due to hydrocephalus from CSF obstruction. May be the presenting sign in young infants.
parent_description: Increased head circumference in infants due to hydrocephalus from CSF obstruction. May be the presenting sign in young infants.

section_description: Headache from increased intracranial pressure due to obstructive hydrocephalus. Often worse in morning and may be accompanied by vomiting.
parent_description: Headache from increased intracranial pressure due to obstructive hydrocephalus. Often worse in morning and may be accompanied by vomiting.

section_description: Cerebellar ataxia with truncal instability and gait disturbance from tumor involvement of cerebellar structures.
parent_description: Cerebellar ataxia with truncal instability and gait disturbance from tumor involvement of cerebellar structures.

section_description: Vomiting, often in the morning, from increased intracranial pressure and brainstem involvement.
parent_description: Vomiting, often in the morning, from increased intracranial pressure and brainstem involvement.

section_description: Optic disc swelling from increased intracranial pressure. May lead to visual symptoms if prolonged.
parent_description: Optic disc swelling from increased intracranial pressure. May lead to visual symptoms if prolonged.

section_description: Episodic or chronic swelling primarily affecting the lips and face. The edema is typically painless and may persist for hours to days before resolving spontaneously.
parent_description: Episodic or chronic swelling primarily affecting the lips and face. The edema is typically painless and may persist for hours to days before resolving spontaneously.

section_description: Facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) paralysis, often recurrent and bilateral alternately. Episodes may be intermittent with resolution, distinguishing MRS from other causes of isolated facial paralysis.
parent_description: Facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) paralysis, often recurrent and bilateral alternately. Episodes may be intermittent with resolution, distinguishing MRS from other causes of isolated facial paralysis.

section_description: Swelling and enlargement of the tongue (macroglossia) with granulomatous changes of oral mucosa. Diffuse mucosal edema with a granular appearance is characteristic.
parent_description: Swelling and enlargement of the tongue (macroglossia) with granulomatous changes of oral mucosa. Diffuse mucosal edema with a granular appearance is characteristic.

section_description: Recurrent migraines with or without aura have been described in rare cases of Melkersson-Rosenthal syndrome, particularly in patients with concurrent SCN1A variants. This represents a rare neurological phenotype suggesting potential overlap between MRS and channelopathy-related disorders.
parent_description: Recurrent migraines with or without aura have been described in rare cases of Melkersson-Rosenthal syndrome, particularly in patients with concurrent SCN1A variants. This represents a rare neurological phenotype suggesting potential overlap between MRS and channelopathy-related disorders.

section_description: Recurrent attacks of spinning vertigo lasting 20 minutes to several hours, often accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Episodes are unpredictable and can be severely debilitating.
parent_description: Recurrent attacks of spinning vertigo lasting 20 minutes to several hours, often accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Episodes are unpredictable and can be severely debilitating.

section_description: Fluctuating, progressive hearing loss initially affecting low frequencies, eventually becoming permanent and affecting all frequencies as the disease progresses.
parent_description: Fluctuating, progressive hearing loss initially affecting low frequencies, eventually becoming permanent and affecting all frequencies as the disease progresses.
raw_json: {"preferred_term": "low-frequency sensorineural hearing impairment", "term": {"id": "HP:0008573", "label": "Low-frequency sensorineural hearing impairment"}}

section_description: Ringing, buzzing, or roaring sounds in the affected ear, often low-pitched and fluctuating. May become constant with disease progression.
parent_description: Ringing, buzzing, or roaring sounds in the affected ear, often low-pitched and fluctuating. May become constant with disease progression.

section_description: Sensation of pressure or fullness in the affected ear, often preceding or accompanying vertiginous episodes.
parent_description: Sensation of pressure or fullness in the affected ear, often preceding or accompanying vertiginous episodes.

section_description: Autonomic symptoms accompanying acute vertigo episodes due to vestibular system dysfunction.
parent_description: Autonomic symptoms accompanying acute vertigo episodes due to vestibular system dysfunction.

section_description: Merkel cell carcinoma is a high-grade neuroendocrine carcinoma with characteristic small round blue cell histology and neuroendocrine marker expression (synaptophysin, chromogranin, CD56).
parent_description: Merkel cell carcinoma is a high-grade neuroendocrine carcinoma with characteristic small round blue cell histology and neuroendocrine marker expression (synaptophysin, chromogranin, CD56).

section_description: Rapidly growing, firm, painless, dome-shaped nodule typically red or violaceous in color. Often described by AEIOU criteria: Asymptomatic, Expanding rapidly, Immunosuppression, Older age, UV-exposed site.
parent_description: Rapidly growing, firm, painless, dome-shaped nodule typically red or violaceous in color. Often described by AEIOU criteria: Asymptomatic, Expanding rapidly, Immunosuppression, Older age, UV-exposed site.
raw_json: {"preferred_term": "Neoplasm of the skin", "term": {"id": "HP:0008069", "label": "Neoplasm of the skin"}}

section_description: Uni- or bilateral coronal suture fusion is the most common feature. Bilateral involvement causes brachycephaly; unilateral causes plagiocephaly.
parent_description: Uni- or bilateral coronal suture fusion is the most common feature. Bilateral involvement causes brachycephaly; unilateral causes plagiocephaly.

section_description: Midface hypoplasia may be present but is typically milder than in Crouzon or Apert syndromes.
parent_description: Midface hypoplasia may be present but is typically milder than in Crouzon or Apert syndromes.

section_description: Sensorineural hearing loss is common and may be progressive. It is an important feature distinguishing Muenke from other craniosynostosis syndromes.
parent_description: Sensorineural hearing loss is common and may be progressive. It is an important feature distinguishing Muenke from other craniosynostosis syndromes.

section_description: Short hands with brachydactyly may occur, though limb involvement is generally mild.
parent_description: Short hands with brachydactyly may occur, though limb involvement is generally mild.

section_description: Fusion of carpal or tarsal bones may be seen on radiographs.
parent_description: Fusion of carpal or tarsal bones may be seen on radiographs.

section_description: Developmental delay or intellectual disability occurs in a subset of patients, though many have normal intelligence.
parent_description: Developmental delay or intellectual disability occurs in a subset of patients, though many have normal intelligence.

section_description: MTC occurs in virtually all MEN2 patients and is the primary cause of morbidity and mortality. Develops from thyroid C-cells that produce calcitonin. Age of onset depends on RET mutation: MEN2B patients may develop MTC in infancy while some FMTC mutations cause later onset. Prophylactic thyroidectomy timing is based on mutation risk category.
parent_description: MTC occurs in virtually all MEN2 patients and is the primary cause of morbidity and mortality. Develops from thyroid C-cells that produce calcitonin. Age of onset depends on RET mutation: MEN2B patients may develop MTC in infancy while some FMTC mutations cause later onset. Prophylactic thyroidectomy timing is based on mutation risk category.

section_description: Pheochromocytomas occur in approximately 50% of MEN2A and MEN2B patients. Often bilateral (50-80%) and may be diagnosed before, concurrent with, or after MTC. Screening with plasma metanephrines is essential before any surgery. Generally benign but can cause hypertensive crises if undiagnosed.
parent_description: Pheochromocytomas occur in approximately 50% of MEN2A and MEN2B patients. Often bilateral (50-80%) and may be diagnosed before, concurrent with, or after MTC. Screening with plasma metanephrines is essential before any surgery. Generally benign but can cause hypertensive crises if undiagnosed.

section_description: Primary hyperparathyroidism occurs in 20-30% of MEN2A patients but not in MEN2B. Usually multigland disease. May be asymptomatic or cause hypercalcemia symptoms. Often milder than MEN1-associated hyperparathyroidism.
parent_description: Primary hyperparathyroidism occurs in 20-30% of MEN2A patients but not in MEN2B. Usually multigland disease. May be asymptomatic or cause hypercalcemia symptoms. Often milder than MEN1-associated hyperparathyroidism.

section_description: Mucosal neuromas of the lips, tongue, and eyelids are characteristic of MEN2B and may be present from early childhood. They produce a distinctive bumpy, nodular appearance of the lips and thickened appearance of the eyelids.
parent_description: Mucosal neuromas of the lips, tongue, and eyelids are characteristic of MEN2B and may be present from early childhood. They produce a distinctive bumpy, nodular appearance of the lips and thickened appearance of the eyelids.

section_description: Diffuse ganglioneuromatosis of the gastrointestinal tract occurs in MEN2B, causing constipation, megacolon, and feeding difficulties from infancy.
parent_description: Diffuse ganglioneuromatosis of the gastrointestinal tract occurs in MEN2B, causing constipation, megacolon, and feeding difficulties from infancy.

section_description: MEN2B patients often have a marfanoid body habitus with tall stature, long limbs, arachnodactyly, pectus excavatum, and high-arched palate. Unlike true Marfan syndrome, they do not have lens dislocation or aortic root dilation.
parent_description: MEN2B patients often have a marfanoid body habitus with tall stature, long limbs, arachnodactyly, pectus excavatum, and high-arched palate. Unlike true Marfan syndrome, they do not have lens dislocation or aortic root dilation.

raw_json: {"preferred_term": "Reduced left ventricular ejection fraction", "term": {"id": "HP:0012664", "label": "Reduced left ventricular ejection fraction"}}

section_description: Worsening of symptoms following physical or mental exertion, often delayed by 24-72 hours and lasting days to weeks.
parent_description: Worsening of symptoms following physical or mental exertion, often delayed by 24-72 hours and lasting days to weeks.

section_description: Profound, debilitating fatigue not substantially alleviated by rest and not explained by other medical conditions.
parent_description: Profound, debilitating fatigue not substantially alleviated by rest and not explained by other medical conditions.

section_description: Difficulties with concentration, short-term memory, and information processing, commonly described as brain fog.
parent_description: Difficulties with concentration, short-term memory, and information processing, commonly described as brain fog.

section_description: Worsening of symptoms upon assuming and maintaining upright posture, including lightheadedness, dizziness, and presyncope.
parent_description: Worsening of symptoms upon assuming and maintaining upright posture, including lightheadedness, dizziness, and presyncope.

section_description: Unrefreshing sleep despite adequate duration, difficulty falling or staying asleep, and altered sleep architecture.
parent_description: Unrefreshing sleep despite adequate duration, difficulty falling or staying asleep, and altered sleep architecture.

section_description: Muscle pain that may be widespread or localized, often worsened after exertion.
parent_description: Muscle pain that may be widespread or localized, often worsened after exertion.

section_description: New or worsened headaches of various types, often triggered by exertion.
parent_description: New or worsened headaches of various types, often triggered by exertion.

section_description: Elevated white blood cell count, though less pronounced than in FLT3-ITD mutated AML.
parent_description: Elevated white blood cell count, though less pronounced than in FLT3-ITD mutated AML.

section_description: Normocytic normochromic anemia from bone marrow replacement and ineffective erythropoiesis.
parent_description: Normocytic normochromic anemia from bone marrow replacement and ineffective erythropoiesis.

section_description: Low platelet count due to bone marrow infiltration by leukemic blasts.
parent_description: Low platelet count due to bone marrow infiltration by leukemic blasts.

section_description: Fatigue related to anemia and systemic effects of leukemia.
parent_description: Fatigue related to anemia and systemic effects of leukemia.

section_description: Increased infection susceptibility from neutropenia and dysfunctional myeloid cells.
parent_description: Increased infection susceptibility from neutropenia and dysfunctional myeloid cells.

section_description: Melanoma arising from cutaneous melanocytes. NRAS-mutant melanomas are typically associated with chronic sun damage sites and may present with thicker primary tumors compared to BRAF-mutant disease.
parent_description: Melanoma arising from cutaneous melanocytes. NRAS-mutant melanomas are typically associated with chronic sun damage sites and may present with thicker primary tumors compared to BRAF-mutant disease.

section_description: Primary tumor presenting as an asymmetric pigmented lesion, often arising on chronically sun-damaged skin in older patients.
parent_description: Primary tumor presenting as an asymmetric pigmented lesion, often arising on chronically sun-damaged skin in older patients.
raw_json: {"preferred_term": "Neoplasm of the skin", "term": {"id": "HP:0008069", "label": "Neoplasm of the skin"}}

section_description: Clinical presentation depends on tumor type and location. NTRK fusions can occur in virtually any solid tumor type.
parent_description: Clinical presentation depends on tumor type and location. NTRK fusions can occur in virtually any solid tumor type.

section_description: Constitutional symptoms are common in advanced disease regardless of tumor histology.
parent_description: Constitutional symptoms are common in advanced disease regardless of tumor histology.

section_description: Painless neck mass from nodal metastases is the most common presenting symptom (60-90% of cases). Often the primary tumor is small and asymptomatic while nodal disease is prominent.
parent_description: Painless neck mass from nodal metastases is the most common presenting symptom (60-90% of cases). Often the primary tumor is small and asymptomatic while nodal disease is prominent.

section_description: Nasal stuffiness and obstruction occur when the tumor enlarges in the nasopharynx, blocking the posterior nares.
parent_description: Nasal stuffiness and obstruction occur when the tumor enlarges in the nasopharynx, blocking the posterior nares.

section_description: Conductive hearing loss and middle ear effusion occur due to eustachian tube obstruction by the nasopharyngeal tumor.
parent_description: Conductive hearing loss and middle ear effusion occur due to eustachian tube obstruction by the nasopharyngeal tumor.

section_description: Nosebleeds may occur from tumor surface ulceration or erosion into blood vessels.
parent_description: Nosebleeds may occur from tumor surface ulceration or erosion into blood vessels.

section_description: Skull base invasion can cause cranial nerve palsies, particularly CN V (trigeminal) causing facial numbness, and CN VI (abducens) causing diplopia. Advanced tumors may involve CN IX-XII.
parent_description: Skull base invasion can cause cranial nerve palsies, particularly CN V (trigeminal) causing facial numbness, and CN VI (abducens) causing diplopia. Advanced tumors may involve CN IX-XII.

section_description: Headache may indicate skull base invasion or intracranial extension.
parent_description: Headache may indicate skull base invasion or intracranial extension.

section_description: An abdominal mass is the most common presentation, typically arising from the adrenal gland or paraspinal sympathetic ganglia. The mass may be incidentally discovered or cause abdominal distension.
parent_description: An abdominal mass is the most common presentation, typically arising from the adrenal gland or paraspinal sympathetic ganglia. The mass may be incidentally discovered or cause abdominal distension.

section_description: Hypertension may occur due to catecholamine secretion by tumor cells or renal artery compression by the tumor mass.
parent_description: Hypertension may occur due to catecholamine secretion by tumor cells or renal artery compression by the tumor mass.

section_description: Fever may occur as a paraneoplastic symptom or with advanced disease.
parent_description: Fever may occur as a paraneoplastic symptom or with advanced disease.

section_description: Weight loss and failure to thrive can occur, particularly with advanced or metastatic disease.
parent_description: Weight loss and failure to thrive can occur, particularly with advanced or metastatic disease.

section_description: Periorbital metastases causing proptosis and periorbital ecchymosis (raccoon eyes) are characteristic of metastatic neuroblastoma.
parent_description: Periorbital metastases causing proptosis and periorbital ecchymosis (raccoon eyes) are characteristic of metastatic neuroblastoma.

section_description: Bone pain from skeletal metastases is common in high-risk neuroblastoma. Metastatic bone disease may cause limping or irritability in young children.
parent_description: Bone pain from skeletal metastases is common in high-risk neuroblastoma. Metastatic bone disease may cause limping or irritability in young children.

section_description: Secretory diarrhea can occur as a paraneoplastic syndrome due to tumor secretion of vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP).
parent_description: Secretory diarrhea can occur as a paraneoplastic syndrome due to tumor secretion of vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP).

section_description: Flat, hyperpigmented skin lesions present in >99% of NF1 patients. Six or more cafe-au-lait macules >5mm (prepubertal) or >15mm (postpubertal) meet one of the NIH diagnostic criteria. Usually present at birth or develop in first years of life.
parent_description: Flat, hyperpigmented skin lesions present in >99% of NF1 patients. Six or more cafe-au-lait macules >5mm (prepubertal) or >15mm (postpubertal) meet one of the NIH diagnostic criteria. Usually present at birth or develop in first years of life.

section_description: Benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors arising from Schwann cells. Typically appear around puberty and increase in number with age. May cause cosmetic concerns but rarely become malignant.
parent_description: Benign peripheral nerve sheath tumors arising from Schwann cells. Typically appear around puberty and increase in number with age. May cause cosmetic concerns but rarely become malignant.

section_description: Diffuse neurofibromas involving multiple nerve fascicles, often present at birth. Can cause significant morbidity through mass effect, disfigurement, and pain. Approximately 8-13% lifetime risk of malignant transformation to MPNST.
parent_description: Diffuse neurofibromas involving multiple nerve fascicles, often present at birth. Can cause significant morbidity through mass effect, disfigurement, and pain. Approximately 8-13% lifetime risk of malignant transformation to MPNST.

section_description: Melanocytic hamartomas of the iris, appearing as tan-brown dome-shaped elevations. Present in >90% of adults with NF1. Best visualized by slit-lamp examination. Pathognomonic for NF1 and do not affect vision.
parent_description: Melanocytic hamartomas of the iris, appearing as tan-brown dome-shaped elevations. Present in >90% of adults with NF1. Best visualized by slit-lamp examination. Pathognomonic for NF1 and do not affect vision.

section_description: Low-grade gliomas of the optic nerve, chiasm, or tract occur in 15-20% of NF1 patients. Usually pilocytic astrocytomas. Most are asymptomatic and nonprogressive, but can cause vision loss. Peak incidence in first 6 years of life.
parent_description: Low-grade gliomas of the optic nerve, chiasm, or tract occur in 15-20% of NF1 patients. Usually pilocytic astrocytomas. Most are asymptomatic and nonprogressive, but can cause vision loss. Peak incidence in first 6 years of life.

section_description: Aggressive sarcoma arising from peripheral nerves, often from transformation of plexiform neurofibromas. Lifetime risk 8-13% in NF1. Leading cause of NF1-related mortality. Presents with rapid growth, pain, or new neurologic deficits.
parent_description: Aggressive sarcoma arising from peripheral nerves, often from transformation of plexiform neurofibromas. Lifetime risk 8-13% in NF1. Leading cause of NF1-related mortality. Presents with rapid growth, pain, or new neurologic deficits.

section_description: Spinal curvature occurs in 10-30% of NF1 patients. Can be idiopathic-type or dystrophic (sharply angulated, short segment) forms. Dystrophic scoliosis may progress rapidly and require surgical intervention.
parent_description: Spinal curvature occurs in 10-30% of NF1 patients. Can be idiopathic-type or dystrophic (sharply angulated, short segment) forms. Dystrophic scoliosis may progress rapidly and require surgical intervention.

section_description: Learning disabilities and attention deficits occur in 50-75% of children with NF1. Intelligence is usually normal but specific learning disabilities, ADHD, and executive function problems are common. Motor coordination difficulties may occur.
parent_description: Learning disabilities and attention deficits occur in 50-75% of children with NF1. Intelligence is usually normal but specific learning disabilities, ADHD, and executive function problems are common. Motor coordination difficulties may occur.

section_description: Inflammation of the optic nerve causing acute vision loss, eye pain, and color vision impairment. Often bilateral and severe in NMOSD compared to MS-associated optic neuritis.
parent_description: Inflammation of the optic nerve causing acute vision loss, eye pain, and color vision impairment. Often bilateral and severe in NMOSD compared to MS-associated optic neuritis.

section_description: Longitudinally extensive transverse myelitis (LETM) affecting three or more vertebral segments is characteristic of NMOSD, distinguishing it from the shorter lesions typical of multiple sclerosis. Causes paraplegia, sensory loss, and bladder/bowel dysfunction. LETM is a core diagnostic criterion for NMOSD.
parent_description: Longitudinally extensive transverse myelitis (LETM) affecting three or more vertebral segments is characteristic of NMOSD, distinguishing it from the shorter lesions typical of multiple sclerosis. Causes paraplegia, sensory loss, and bladder/bowel dysfunction. LETM is a core diagnostic criterion for NMOSD.

section_description: Intractable nausea, vomiting, and hiccups due to inflammation of the area postrema (UBERON:0002162) in the dorsal medulla. A characteristic early manifestation that may precede other symptoms. This is a syndrome involving a specific anatomical location rather than a simple phenotype.
parent_description: Intractable nausea, vomiting, and hiccups due to inflammation of the area postrema (UBERON:0002162) in the dorsal medulla. A characteristic early manifestation that may precede other symptoms. This is a syndrome involving a specific anatomical location rather than a simple phenotype.

section_description: Widely spaced eyes are a characteristic facial feature of Noonan syndrome.
parent_description: Widely spaced eyes are a characteristic facial feature of Noonan syndrome.

section_description: Downward slanting of the eye openings is a common facial feature.
parent_description: Downward slanting of the eye openings is a common facial feature.

section_description: Drooping of the upper eyelids is frequently observed.
parent_description: Drooping of the upper eyelids is frequently observed.

section_description: Posteriorly rotated, low-set ears are characteristic.
parent_description: Posteriorly rotated, low-set ears are characteristic.

section_description: Excess skin on the lateral neck creating a webbed appearance.
parent_description: Excess skin on the lateral neck creating a webbed appearance.

section_description: Dysplastic pulmonary valve stenosis is the most common cardiac defect, occurring in approximately 50-60% of patients. Associated with PTPN11 and SOS1 genotypes.
parent_description: Dysplastic pulmonary valve stenosis is the most common cardiac defect, occurring in approximately 50-60% of patients. Associated with PTPN11 and SOS1 genotypes.

section_description: Left ventricular hypertrophy occurring in approximately 20% of patients overall, but up to 70-95% in those with RAF1 or RIT1 mutations. Can be present at birth or develop during infancy.
parent_description: Left ventricular hypertrophy occurring in approximately 20% of patients overall, but up to 70-95% in those with RAF1 or RIT1 mutations. Can be present at birth or develop during infancy.

section_description: Atrial septal defects occur in 6-10% of individuals with Noonan syndrome.
parent_description: Atrial septal defects occur in 6-10% of individuals with Noonan syndrome.

section_description: Postnatal growth retardation resulting in adult height typically at or below the third percentile for the general population. Linked to RAS/MAPK effects on GH signaling and chondrocyte differentiation.
parent_description: Postnatal growth retardation resulting in adult height typically at or below the third percentile for the general population. Linked to RAS/MAPK effects on GH signaling and chondrocyte differentiation.

section_description: Chest wall deformities including pectus excavatum and pectus carinatum are common.
parent_description: Chest wall deformities including pectus excavatum and pectus carinatum are common.

section_description: Undescended testes in males is a common finding.
parent_description: Undescended testes in males is a common finding.

section_description: Coagulation defects including factor XI deficiency and platelet dysfunction, leading to easy bruising and prolonged bleeding after surgery or trauma.
parent_description: Coagulation defects including factor XI deficiency and platelet dysfunction, leading to easy bruising and prolonged bleeding after surgery or trauma.

section_description: Peripheral lymphedema and central conducting lymphatic anomalies occur in a substantial minority. ERK/SOX18 signaling axis is implicated in lymphatic dysplasia.
parent_description: Peripheral lymphedema and central conducting lymphatic anomalies occur in a substantial minority. ERK/SOX18 signaling axis is implicated in lymphatic dysplasia.

section_description: Mild cognitive impairment and motor delays are common, with learning disabilities in approximately 25% of individuals.
parent_description: Mild cognitive impairment and motor delays are common, with learning disabilities in approximately 25% of individuals.

section_description: Approximately 15-35% of individuals have mild intellectual disability.
parent_description: Approximately 15-35% of individuals have mild intellectual disability.

section_description: Many infants experience feeding difficulties and failure to thrive in early life.
parent_description: Many infants experience feeding difficulties and failure to thrive in early life.
raw_json: {"preferred_term": "Feeding difficulties in infancy", "term": {"id": "HP:0008872", "label": "Feeding difficulties in infancy"}}

section_description: Blue or blue-gray scleral hue is characteristic and persists into adulthood, distinguishing type I from type IV OI where sclerae normalize with age.
parent_description: Blue or blue-gray scleral hue is characteristic and persists into adulthood, distinguishing type I from type IV OI where sclerae normalize with age.

section_description: Increased bone fragility leads to fractures, often with minimal trauma. Fracture frequency is variable and typically decreases after puberty.
parent_description: Increased bone fragility leads to fractures, often with minimal trauma. Fracture frequency is variable and typically decreases after puberty.

section_description: Height is typically in the low-normal range, distinguishing type I from the more severe forms with significant short stature.
parent_description: Height is typically in the low-normal range, distinguishing type I from the more severe forms with significant short stature.

section_description: Progressive hearing loss develops in approximately 50% of adults with OI type I, typically beginning in the second or third decade.
parent_description: Progressive hearing loss develops in approximately 50% of adults with OI type I, typically beginning in the second or third decade.

section_description: Generalized joint hypermobility due to connective tissue laxity.
parent_description: Generalized joint hypermobility due to connective tissue laxity.

section_description: Increased tendency to bruise due to connective tissue fragility.
parent_description: Increased tendency to bruise due to connective tissue fragility.

section_description: Numerous fractures present at birth, including ribs, long bones, and skull. Fractures occur in utero from normal fetal movements.
parent_description: Numerous fractures present at birth, including ribs, long bones, and skull. Fractures occur in utero from normal fetal movements.

section_description: Dark blue or gray sclerae due to extreme thinning, allowing visualization of underlying choroidal pigment.
parent_description: Dark blue or gray sclerae due to extreme thinning, allowing visualization of underlying choroidal pigment.

section_description: Extreme shortening of all limbs due to multiple fractures and impaired bone formation.
parent_description: Extreme shortening of all limbs due to multiple fractures and impaired bone formation.

section_description: Multiple rib fractures produce characteristic beaded appearance on imaging.
parent_description: Multiple rib fractures produce characteristic beaded appearance on imaging.

section_description: Underdeveloped lungs secondary to small thoracic cage, contributing to perinatal lethality.
parent_description: Underdeveloped lungs secondary to small thoracic cage, contributing to perinatal lethality.

section_description: Multiple wormian (intrasutural) bones in the skull due to defective ossification.
parent_description: Multiple wormian (intrasutural) bones in the skull due to defective ossification.

section_description: Profound growth deficiency with adult height often under 100 cm due to progressive skeletal deformity and impaired bone growth.
parent_description: Profound growth deficiency with adult height often under 100 cm due to progressive skeletal deformity and impaired bone growth.

section_description: Progressive bowing of long bones, kyphoscoliosis, and chest wall deformities that worsen with repeated fractures and weight bearing.
parent_description: Progressive bowing of long bones, kyphoscoliosis, and chest wall deformities that worsen with repeated fractures and weight bearing.
raw_json: {"preferred_term": "Abnormality of the skeletal system", "term": {"id": "HP:0000924", "label": "Abnormality of the skeletal system"}}

section_description: Hundreds of fractures over a lifetime, occurring with minimal trauma.
parent_description: Hundreds of fractures over a lifetime, occurring with minimal trauma.

section_description: Abnormal dentin formation producing opalescent, discolored teeth that are prone to breakage. Present in most type III patients.
parent_description: Abnormal dentin formation producing opalescent, discolored teeth that are prone to breakage. Present in most type III patients.

section_description: Characteristic triangular face shape with prominent forehead and underdeveloped midface.
parent_description: Characteristic triangular face shape with prominent forehead and underdeveloped midface.

section_description: Progressive spinal curvature contributing to respiratory compromise and mobility limitations.
parent_description: Progressive spinal curvature contributing to respiratory compromise and mobility limitations.

section_description: Progressive hearing loss, often beginning in childhood.
parent_description: Progressive hearing loss, often beginning in childhood.

section_description: Sclerae may be blue at birth but often normalize during childhood.
parent_description: Sclerae may be blue at birth but often normalize during childhood.

section_description: Variable short stature, typically mild to moderate. Some individuals achieve near-normal height.
parent_description: Variable short stature, typically mild to moderate. Some individuals achieve near-normal height.
